==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Revile
<hw>Re*vile"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t. & i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Reviled</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Reviling</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[Pref. <ets>re-</ets> +
OF. <ets>aviler</ets> to make vile, depreciate, F. <ets>avilir</ets>;
⟦agrave⟧ (L. <ets>ad</ets>.) + <ets>vil</ets> vile. See
<er>Vile</er>.]</ety> <def>To address or abuse with opprobrious and
contemptuous language; to reproach.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧And did not she herself
<xex>revile</xex> me there?⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who, when he was <qex>reviled</qex>, <qex>reviled</qex> not
again.</q> <rj><qau>1 Pet. ii. 23.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To reproach; vilify; upbraid;
calumniate.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revile</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Revile
<hw>Re*vile"</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <def>Reproach; reviling.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The gracious Judge, without <qex>revile</qex>, replied.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Revilement</ent>⟦br⟧
